Analyzing Mental Health Disorder Prevalence in the United States¶

Introduction¶

In recent years, we have seen a paradigm shift in how we consider mental health as a part of our daily lives. While it remains shrouded in social stigma to some extent, professionals in the healthcare field have long since reached a strong consensus that indeed, mental health is important to our well-being. In many ways, it can influence our physical health, further driving the fact that it must remain a top priority to our well-being.

Of the many mental health disorders, two stand out as some of the most well-known: anxiety and depression. Both are uniquely defined yet comorbid with one another. In any case, given that they both interrupt an individual's ability to function properly, it remains an important topic to address in today's world.

As such, in this tutorial, we will analyze how prevalent anxiety and depression are in the United States. In doing so, we can begin to answer various questions: What are the most susceptible demographics to anxiety or depression? How do various states compare? Has there been a noticeable increase or decrease over time?

Data Collection¶

The dataset we will be using in this tutorial comes from the Household Pulse Survey, a collaborative effort from the National Center for Health Statistics and five other federal agencies. This dataset is updated frequently, with results ranging from as early as April 23, 2020, to November 14, 2022. With this in mind, if you are following this tutorial in the far-off future, you may be able to draw new insights as this dataset gets updated over time!

To begin, we will need to import some Python packages that will help us during our data analysis. In particular:

  • pandas
  • numpy
  • folium
  • matplotlib
  • datetime
  • requests
  • BeautifulSoup
  • re

First, we should take a look at our dataset to get a sense of what exactly we will be working with.

Okay! We have our dataset all ready for us to use. But what exactly are we working with? What does each row and column represent?

  • Indicator: Symptom(s) surveyed. May be anxiety, depression, or whether a participant has at least one.
  • Group: The survey's intended focus group/audience. They may group by age, state, race/ethnicity, etc.
  • State: The state of focus. "United States" may also be marked here for a survey of the whole country.
  • Subgroup: A narrower group within the existing Group category. For example, if we group by education, we may only want to view those who have a high school level education.
  • Phase: A time period in which the survey was conducted, spanning various Time Period groups.
  • Time Period: A purely numerical way to index the Time Period Label column.
  • Time Period Label: A description of when survey data was collected.
  • Time Period Start Data: The start date of when a survey was conducted.
  • Time Period End Data: The end date of when a survey was conducted.
  • Value: The percentage of participants who indicated positive for the Indicator.
  • Low CI: Low confidence interval.
  • High CI: High confidence interval.
  • Confidence Interval: The range of values that, if the study was performed again, may fall into.
  • Quartile Range: Range of data divisions.

Data Management¶

For this tutorial's purposes, we will not need columns that deal with phases, confidence intervals, and quartile ranges. We can also remove redundant columns, such as Time Period Label. We should also ensure that any missing data is removed.

Also, since we're analyzing mental health as a whole rather than just one disorder, we should just pull our data from rows that have a Symptoms of Anxiety Disorder or Depressive Disorder indicator!

To draw conclusions about our data, we first have to understand what we are working with. What do our groups and subgroups look like?

In [4]:
def get_groups_and_subgroups(print_flag, return_flag):
    subgroup_dict = {}
    for group,idx in df_either.groupby("Group"):
        subgroup_arr = []
        if(print_flag):
            print("GROUP \"" + str(group) + "\" has " + str(len(idx)) + " rows with the following subgroups...")
        for i in idx['Subgroup'].unique():
            if(print_flag):
                print("\t" + str(i))
            subgroup_arr.append(str(i))
        subgroup_dict[str(group)] = tuple(subgroup_arr) # Because lists can't a key in a dictionary in Python, we do something sneaky with a tuple.
    if(return_flag):
        return subgroup_dict
    else:
        return

get_groups_and_subgroups(print_flag=True, return_flag=False) # Ignore the result, we don't want a dictionary of our groups and subgroups just yet.

Looks like we have quite a bit to parse through. Before analyzing our data, we should probably clear up one little discrepancy: the National Estimate group. It seems pointless to keep it alone with one subgroup, so we should put it in the By State group to better compare how the U.S. performs versus its states.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Let's first gather some basic data about each of our subgroups and groups. In particular, finding the count, mean, median, and standard deviation of each subgroup can help us see some trends in our dataset.

In [6]:
def get_statistic_of_subgroup(df, subgroup, function):
    arr = []
    # Go through each row that matches the subgroup we're looking for.
    for idx,row in df[df['Subgroup']==subgroup].iterrows():
        # We want to apply some function to our subgroup's Value data, so we add it to a temporary list.
        arr.append(row['Value'])
    # Apply the function parameter to our array!
    return function(arr)

for group in subgroup_dict:
    subgroup_arr = list(subgroup_dict[group])
    print("=== Statistics " + group + " ===")
    for subgroup in subgroup_arr:
        print("\t -- SUBGROUP: " + subgroup + " --")
        print("\t\tCount: " + str(get_statistic_of_subgroup(df_either, subgroup, len)))
        print("\t\tMean: " + str(get_statistic_of_subgroup(df_either, subgroup, np.mean)))
        print("\t\tMedian: " + str(get_statistic_of_subgroup(df_either, subgroup, np.median)))
        print("\t\tMax: " + str(get_statistic_of_subgroup(df_either, subgroup, np.max)))
        print("\t\tStandard Deviation: " + str(get_statistic_of_subgroup(df_either, subgroup, np.std)))
    print("\n")

We have our first insights into our dataset!

On a general sense of scale, it looks like the mean and median for most subgroups are very close to one another. We may only see slight deviations, but as a whole, this means that our data in our Value column is relatively balanced or symmetric, i.e., we do not have many outliers. What also stands out is that thankfully, the data gathered for each subgroup is even throughout all groups. This ensures that any insights drawn from certain subgroups are not a result of sampling bias (say, for example, we had 50 rows of data for Maryland and only one row of data for all other states).

Taking a closer look, we can observe a few noticeable trends:

  • Age seems to play a significant role, as it appears that the younger someone is, the higher likelihood they are of having anxiety or depressive disorder symptoms.
  • Disability status, sexual orientation, and gender identity each have one clear subgroup that shows the most symptoms on average, along with higher maximums.
  • Education does not have a clear trend as Age does since on average, people of the Some college/Associate's Degree subgroup showed more symptoms than those of High school diploma or GED.
  • It is currently unclear whether the Non-Hispanic, other races and multiple races subgroup shows the most symptoms as a result of including several races or simply by demographics.

Data Visualization of all Groups¶

While this basic data helps identify some trends across those who may suffer from anxiety or depression, it is rather surface-level and difficult to take in all of this information at once. Specifically, the By State subgroup suffers the most from information overloadwe have fifty states to weigh, along with a national estimate!

To better compare our subgroups, let's visualize the averages of our values with bar plots!

Data Visualization By State¶

To visualize our data using maps, we'll be using the folium library. Specifically, we'll be aiming to show how each state's symptomatic averages stand across the United States. As such, we'll also be leaving out the National Estimate from this visualization.

In [9]:
url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/python-visualization/folium/master/examples/data"
state_geo = f"{url}/us-states.json" # Necessary to properly show the U.S. states!
state_subgroup_arr = list(subgroup_dict["By State"])
state_subgroup_arr.remove("United States")
def create_df_choropleth(df):
    df_choropleth = df.copy(deep=True) # Temporary, dummy DataFrame just for this one use.
    df_choropleth["Subgroup"] = df["Subgroup"].apply(lambda x: x if x in state_subgroup_arr else np.nan)
    df_choropleth = df_choropleth.dropna()
    # Choropleth maps take U.S. states via their abbreviations, so we need to reduce each full state name to its abbreviation!
    df_choropleth["Subgroup"] = df_choropleth["Subgroup"].apply(lambda x: state_to_initials.get(x))
    return df_choropleth
df_choropleth = create_df_choropleth(df_either)

def create_map_from_df(df, color, legend):
    m = folium.Map(location=[48, -102], zoom_start=3)
    folium.Choropleth(
        geo_data=state_geo,
        name="choropleth",
        data=df,
        columns=["Subgroup", "Value"],
        key_on="feature.id",
        fill_color=color,
        fill_opacity=0.8,
        line_opacity=0.6,
        legend_name=legend,
    ).add_to(m)
    folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)
    display(m)

Analyzing Symptoms over Time¶

Having analyzed several trends of groups and subgroups and visualized them, we have conveniently left out how much time plays a role in mental health disorder symptoms. Do we see a general increase, decrease, or some other trend in average symptom prevalence over time? Let's find out!

First off, let's just get a general sense of how time influences symptom prevalence. For now, we will not look at any specific subgroupsinstead, we will plot our line graph solely on the values of the average of each unique Time Period End Date.

In [13]:
def get_statistic_of_period(df, period, function):
    arr = []
    for idx,row in df[df['Time Period End Date']==period].iterrows():
        arr.append(row['Value'])
    return function(arr)
def plot_average_values_over_time(datetime_period_arr, period_avg_values_arr):
    plt.plot(datetime_period_arr, period_avg_values_arr)
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%m-%d-%y'))
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.DayLocator(interval=50))
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_tick_params(rotation=45)
    plt.gca().set_xbound(datetime_period_arr[0], datetime_period_arr[len(datetime_period_arr)-1])
    plt.show()

period_arr = df_either['Time Period End Date'].unique()
period_avg_values_arr = []
for period in period_arr:
    period_avg_values_arr.append(get_statistic_of_period(df_either, period, np.mean))
# We'll use datetimes instead of strings for our x-axis!
string_to_datetime = lambda x: dt.datetime.strptime(x, '%m/%d/%Y')
datetime_period_arr = list(map(string_to_datetime, period_arr))
plot_average_values_over_time(datetime_period_arr, period_avg_values_arr)

The sharp decline in anxiety and depressive symptoms at around February 8, 2021, immediately stands out in this line plot. Not only does the decline last until around May 19, 2021, but from then on, the number of symptoms shown never reaches its past heights again.

This plot might be somewhat blown out of proportion, considering that this graph only shows at most around a 12% decline on average across all surveys, but the fact remains that some factors between February 2021 and May 2021 contributed to a sharp decline lasting several months.

So what is this factor? Could be a product of one indicator (anxiety or depression) weighed more heavily? Let's try and find out!

In [16]:
def get_statistic_of_subgroup_and_period(df, subgroup, period, function):
    arr = []
    for idx,row in df[(df['Subgroup']==subgroup) & (df['Time Period End Date']==period)].iterrows():
        arr.append(row['Value'])
    return function(arr)

for group in subgroup_dict:
    subgroup_arr = list(subgroup_dict[group])
    for subgroup in subgroup_arr:
        stat_arr = []
        for period in period_arr:
            stat_arr.append(get_statistic_of_subgroup_and_period(df_either, subgroup, period, np.mean))

    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1,1), loc="upper left")
    plt.show()

On a general scale from our subgroups, our findings from our earlier bar graph visualizations hold up across time as well. There remains a correlation between age and symptoms, disabled persons are more likely to be symptomatic than those who are not, and so on.

Even by breaking our problem down into groups and subgroups, we can still witness the sharp decline as seen in a general overview of anxiety and depressive symptoms. Although we do see three groups that do not follow this exact trend (By Disability status, By Gender identity, and By Sex), we can pinpoint the reasoning behind this: missing data.

Remember our earlier data collection, where we assessed our data and gave counts for how many rows consisted of a certain subgroup? There were fifty-one total phases in which data was collected, in which the three aforementioned groups were the only ones (aside from the dropped National Estimate group) that did not have survey results for every phase.

However, even putting aside the fact that we still do not have a good explanation for this trend, we are also left with a similar issue as before: our line graph for the By State group does not help us visualize how states perform over time. As such, for our final visualization, we will use a heat map to show mental health symptom prevalence across time. relies on the HeatMapOverTime folium plugin, in which we'll need to organize some data and time periods to properly create our map.

Each state appears to fluctuate on its own, but we do see some familiar clusters as shown in our previous map. The Midwest generally shows less symptoms even over time, while regions such as the East Coast and South tend to fluctuate. After around February 2021, we do witness some decline in symptoms overall, but each state tends to operate individually in their trends. Although this map is an improvement over our cluttered line plot from earlier, we do not gain much insight into determining what could be the root of the sudden drop in symptom prevalence.

Conclusions¶

In our attempts to understand how prevalent anxiety and depressive symptoms are in the United States, we have seen notable and distinct trends, but without much explanation as to how they came to be. At the very least, however, what we do know can lead to helpful policymaking or actions for the future. In particular, we would want to investigate further into why certain subgroups show much higher rates of symptoms than others (disabled people, transgender people, bisexual people, and so on). This would be instrumental in providing them more resources to cope with their potential disorders.

One notable aspect that has not been discussed up until now involves the slow uptick of symptom prevalence around July 2021. We do have an explanation for this, as explained by the CDC's Household Pulse Survey site:

Beginning in Phase 3.2 (July 21, 2021) of data collection and reporting, the question reference period changed from the last 7 days to the last two weeks, as typical for this scale.

By extending the reach in which symptoms could appear, it is natural to see how symptom prevalence would increase over time. However, this explanation still leaves us unsure as to what could have caused the sharp decline from early 2021a trend that persists even among subgroups.

As far as the geographical aspect of this study, we witnessed some clustering and some regions that show more symptoms than others. Unfortunately, because our dataset only provides individual state information for subgroups for only the By State group, we cannot test the interactions between other subgroups.

Despite our shortcomings in analyzing this dataset, we still have a decent footing in how to proceed if we would want to investigate this topic further.
